<div class="container">
    <h1 class="text-center">HTTP Protocol - Part 2: Status Codes & Headers</h1>

    <div class="beginner-note">
        <div class="beginner-note-icon">
            <i class="fas fa-comments"></i>
        </div>
        <div class="beginner-note-content">
            <h4>Think of HTTP Status Codes Like Restaurant Responses</h4>
            <p><strong>Status Codes = How the server replies to your request</strong></p>
            <p><strong>Simple analogy:</strong></p>
            <ul>
                <li>"200 OK" = "Here's your food, enjoy!" (Success)</li>
                <li>"404 Not Found" = "Sorry, we don't have that item" (Error)</li>
                <li>"500 Internal Server Error" = "Kitchen is on fire!" (Server problem)</li>
            </ul>
            <p><strong>In web terms:</strong> Status codes tell you exactly what happened with your request!</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="intro-section">
        <p>In <strong>HTTP Part 2</strong>, we'll explore how servers respond to requests. You'll learn about status codes (like 404), headers (extra information), and how HTTP handles different situations.</p>
        
        <div class="alert alert-info">
            <i class="fas fa-lightbulb"></i> <strong>Remember:</strong> HTTP is a conversation. Part 1 was about asking questions (requests), Part 2 is about getting answers (responses)!
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2 class="text-center">HTTP Response: What Servers Send Back</h2>
    
    <div class="http-response-demo">
